WEBVTT

00:03.362 --> 00:10.449
The scripture today is found in the 26th chapter of the Gospel of Matthew, beginning to read verse 69.

00:10.990 --> 00:17.977
Now Peter was sitting out in the courtyard and the servant girl came to him.

00:18.898 --> 00:21.500
You also were there with Jesus of Nazareth, she said.

00:23.542 --> 00:25.264
But he denied it all before them all.

00:26.025 --> 00:27.987
I don't know what you're talking about, he said.

00:29.629 --> 00:31.090
Then he went up the gateway

00:31.842 --> 00:37.688
where another servant girl saw him and said to the people there, this fellow was with Jesus in Nazareth.

00:39.470 --> 00:40.351
He denied it again.

00:40.451 --> 00:42.414
Oh, I don't know the man.

00:42.474 --> 00:50.983
After a little while, those standing there went up to Peter and said, surely you're one of them.

00:51.003 --> 00:52.324
Your accent gives you away.

00:54.306 --> 00:56.929
Then he began to call down curses in his water.

00:57.250 --> 00:58.811
I don't know the man.

00:58.851 --> 01:01.234
Immediately,

01:01.346 --> 01:02.187
A rooster crowed.

01:03.889 --> 01:06.493
Then Peter remembered the word Jesus had spoken.

01:06.533 --> 01:10.838
Before the rooster crowed, you will disown me three times.

01:11.899 --> 01:14.443
And he went outside and wept bitterly.

01:16.946 --> 01:22.934
Early in the morning, all the chief priests and the elders of the people made their plans on how to have Jesus executed.

01:24.616 --> 01:29.522
So they bound him, let him away, and handed him over to Pilate, the governor.

01:31.074 --> 01:40.964
When Judas, who had betrayed him, saw that Jesus was condemned, he was seized with remorse and returned the 30 pieces of silver, the chief priests and the others.

01:42.065 --> 01:46.329
I have sinned, he said, for I have betrayed innocent blood.

01:47.951 --> 01:49.613
What is that to us, the replied?

01:49.893 --> 01:51.274
That's your responsibility.

01:53.216 --> 01:55.619
So Judas threw the money into the temple and left.

01:57.060 --> 01:59.122
Then he went away and hanged himself.

02:00.610 --> 02:07.419
The chief priests picked up the coins and said, it's against the law to put this into treasury, since it's blood money.

02:09.622 --> 02:14.228
So they decided to use the money to buy the potter's fields as a burial place for foreigners.

02:15.449 --> 02:18.794
That is why it has been called the field of blood to this day.

02:20.396 --> 02:22.959
Then what was spoken by Jeremiah Profits fulfilled.

02:23.860 --> 02:28.146
They took the 30 pieces of silver, priced at him by the people of Israel.

02:28.802 --> 02:32.686
And they used them to buy the potter's field as the Lord commanded me.

02:33.728 --> 02:35.169
This is the word of the Lord.

02:43.959 --> 02:44.800
Good morning, church.

02:44.980 --> 02:46.382
Great to be with you this morning.

02:47.003 --> 02:53.330
And as a rather geeky individual, it's great to start off with a story about video games.

02:54.082 --> 02:58.166
Let's go back to the 1980s or as the teens today call it the 1900s.

02:58.186 --> 03:10.880
The 1980s early on Atari was considered the king of the video game space, but they had come upon hard times financially.

03:11.581 --> 03:23.634
So when the company acquired the rights to Steven Spielberg's famous movie E.T., they figured that the resulting video game title would be the savior of their company.

03:24.322 --> 03:28.347
So, full of confidence, Atari rushed production of this game.

03:29.028 --> 03:34.354
Start to finish in five weeks time, and they produced millions of copies in time for the Christmas rush.

03:35.095 --> 03:38.900
The problem was, the game was a disaster.

03:40.041 --> 03:48.351
It was full of glitches, very confusing, and the entire video game base of popularity said, we hate it.

03:49.072 --> 03:54.098
And more than dislike, it betrayed the source material.

03:54.690 --> 04:02.018
And so, Atari, deeply embarrassed, figured out a way to disown this product.

04:03.079 --> 04:09.306
Late one night, in secret, they hired a fleet of trucks, and they filled that fleet of trucks with millions of copies of the game.

04:09.886 --> 04:14.391
They drove it out to a landfill in the middle of the New Mexico desert where they buried them.

04:15.332 --> 04:20.978
After running over them with steam rollers to crush them, and then covered them in concrete.

04:21.986 --> 04:30.438
The thing that Atari thought was going to solidify its empire ended up costing it a lot of social capital.

04:31.620 --> 04:37.969
And therefore, they went to great lengths to disown the video game that they once called their savior.

04:39.952 --> 04:49.426
Church, we are very quick as human beings to disown the things that we once loved when they start to cost us something.

04:50.850 --> 04:55.235
Today, we are looking at these stories from this passage of Scripture in Matthew.

04:55.275 --> 05:13.074
The stories of Peter and Judas set side by side in their last recorded moments before the death of Jesus, and both disown Jesus in their own way, both respond with their own form of sorrow, and both are hopeless to redeem themselves.

05:14.536 --> 05:20.562
And their stories remind us of what we are all capable of, in fact, guilty of.

05:21.762 --> 05:26.707
which is disowning our savior when the relationship costs us something.

05:29.090 --> 05:31.773
We're continuing our stories through the book of Matthew.

05:32.434 --> 05:37.940
We're in our nine week series and we're dead in the middle right now, looking at these two stories.

05:38.821 --> 05:48.972
And as we continue this, today we're gonna find that regret is limited and remorse can be lethal, but redemption is liberating.

05:49.953 --> 05:51.154
So let's turn to prayer.

05:51.746 --> 05:56.371
We often say, prayer is speaking to God and listening for his voice.

05:56.391 --> 06:06.362
So as we do this, join me and invite the Lord to reveal something to you today about yourself and about his relationship that he longs to have with you.

06:07.243 --> 06:07.704
Let's pray.

06:08.585 --> 06:13.210
Jesus, as we look at these stories today, open our hearts to see ourselves as we truly are.

06:14.732 --> 06:20.178
Help us to move past the regret and the remorse for our failings and sin that we often feel.

06:21.026 --> 06:24.931
and toward the redemption that can be found only in you.

06:26.172 --> 06:28.615
So speak to us now through your word and through your spirit.

06:29.276 --> 06:30.618
In Jesus name, amen.

06:33.461 --> 06:40.710
So just hours before this story takes place, Jesus had predicted both the betrayal of Judas and the denial of Peter.

06:42.012 --> 06:46.698
In the moment, Peter had made a fervent declaration of his loyalty.

06:47.659 --> 06:50.162
Even if all else fall away,

06:50.402 --> 06:52.104
I never will, Jesus.

06:53.346 --> 06:56.210
But in the Garden of Gethsemane, well, Jesus is in agony.

06:56.290 --> 06:58.293
Peter falls asleep three times.

06:59.234 --> 07:06.765
And Jesus diagnoses Peter as having good intentions, but lacking the moral fortitude to follow through.

07:06.805 --> 07:13.193
And he says, the spirit is willing, but the flesh is weak.

07:13.213 --> 07:19.442
When the soldiers arrive to arrest Jesus, Peter tries to fix this God-sized problem with a human-sized solution.

07:19.746 --> 07:23.510
pulls out his sword and he cuts off the ear of one of the high priest servants.

07:24.932 --> 07:30.659
But after Jesus rebukes that violence, Peter's bravado seems to fade quite a bit.

07:31.680 --> 07:36.526
And soon after all of the disciples, including Peter, have now fled from Jesus' side.

07:37.647 --> 07:46.898
And then we come to this passage, which takes place in the palatial estate of the high priest and the courtyard of that facility.

07:47.970 --> 07:51.957
The council of religious leaders have gathered for their mock trial to condemn Jesus.

07:52.718 --> 07:57.306
And this text paints a picture of proximity for both Judas and Peter.

07:57.907 --> 08:04.418
Judas is part of the in crowd now, having successfully traded his relationship with Jesus for his 30 pieces of silver.

08:05.119 --> 08:11.890
He's close enough to the action to bear witness visually to the condemnation that he helped facilitate.

08:12.802 --> 08:25.735
Meanwhile, Peter is keeping his distance and lingering in the courtyard just outside around a fire to stay warm as the proceedings happen in eyeshot and earshot of all that's going on with Jesus.

08:27.256 --> 08:37.366
And while Jesus is being tried inside for who he claims to be, Peter's facing a trial of his own outside in the courtyard for who he was with.

08:39.028 --> 08:41.330
So we're gonna begin by looking at Peter's story.

08:42.114 --> 08:43.375
and how regret is limited.

08:44.937 --> 08:48.840
So when I was a kid, my parents enrolled me in all kinds of different extracurricular activities.

08:49.001 --> 08:54.746
I was in guitar lessons, and swimming, and soccer, and gymnastics, and computer classes, and art lessons, and all of this sort of thing.

08:55.467 --> 08:56.468
And I'm very grateful for it.

08:57.629 --> 09:01.973
But with a dance teacher as a mom, as a child, that included dance lessons.

09:03.014 --> 09:07.819
And as you might imagine, it took a little bit of courage to even say that from this stage.

09:08.880 --> 09:11.442
But when high school was on the horizon,

09:11.810 --> 09:20.583
I knew that even if this gave me some rhythm at a wedding reception, this could be used for social torture.

09:21.004 --> 09:23.147
So I did not speak of it ever.

09:24.269 --> 09:30.358
So it came as a wild shock when some student out of the blue one day said, didn't you take dance lessons as a kid?

09:31.660 --> 09:34.264
I was really embarrassed and totally caught off guard.

09:34.284 --> 09:35.686
And so I denied it outright.

09:36.047 --> 09:36.488
No way.

09:36.528 --> 09:37.449
Not me.

09:39.773 --> 09:40.754
But they kept pressing.

09:40.834 --> 09:41.835
They told other people.

09:42.696 --> 09:44.398
And so I doubled down on my lie.

09:44.999 --> 09:47.602
I swore that was not something I did as a kid.

09:49.964 --> 09:51.986
Well, the bullying intensified and it continued.

09:52.607 --> 10:01.197
And eventually what I found myself doing was attaching to my lie vulgarity and verbal assaults against my accusers.

10:02.578 --> 10:09.426
And eventually I became a version of myself that I actually despised and that deeply dishonored God in my school setting.

10:12.130 --> 10:17.479
This thing that had begun to cost me social standing was a truth.

10:19.923 --> 10:25.592
In Matthew chapter 26, Peter's exposed for a truth that could cost him everything.

10:27.174 --> 10:30.399
And he too became a version of himself that he later despised.

10:31.842 --> 10:36.429
Disowning Jesus usually isn't a singular catastrophic choice.

10:37.871 --> 10:39.474
It's more like a slippery slope.

10:41.058 --> 10:44.503
that starts subtle and ends profane.

10:46.546 --> 11:00.667
Just hours before, after declaring Jesus to be as high as the legions in the safety of the upper room, Peter finds himself in this high priest courtyard close enough to see the action but keeping a very calculated distance.

11:01.869 --> 11:06.296
And Peter's first trial is private association.

11:07.537 --> 11:10.642
A servant girl asks a low stakes question,

11:11.746 --> 11:16.272
And Peter responds with evasion, feigned ignorance.

11:17.594 --> 11:19.296
I don't know what you're talking about, he says.

11:23.422 --> 11:40.786
This is as subtle as remaining silent when Jesus is being mocked in the workplace or pretending like you don't go to church when your neighbor asks what you leave for every Sunday morning or changing the topic when religion comes up on a date or not praying at meal time when guests come over.

11:42.914 --> 11:56.230
Where in your life does private association with Jesus make it just easier to stay vague than become known as a Christian?

12:01.296 --> 12:04.480
Next, the private association moves to public recognition.

12:05.201 --> 12:12.530
Peter retreats to the gateway away from the revealing light of the fire that was keeping him warm and nearer to the exit

12:12.866 --> 12:13.907
A move of safety.

12:15.109 --> 12:20.936
But he's recognized by another servant, who this time points him out to all the others gathered there.

12:21.777 --> 12:29.486
And so Peter disowns Jesus with an oath, an appeal ironically to the divine.

12:31.209 --> 12:32.791
I don't know the man, he says.

12:33.311 --> 12:38.898
And this is like vowing to leave your faith at home in order to land the dream job.

12:39.650 --> 12:51.087
or promising your friends that you'll never let Jesus get between you, or swearing to God that you're not a Christian to preserve your reputation at the gym.

12:54.072 --> 13:00.762
Where might public recognition for your faith cost you something that you fear to lose?

13:05.509 --> 13:08.754
Finally, what began as private and moved to public

13:09.634 --> 13:11.396
becomes personal confrontation.

13:12.778 --> 13:22.289
In fact, John's gospel tells us that Peter's accusers now include an eyewitness from the arrest in the garden, a relative nonetheless of the man whose ear Peter just cut off.

13:23.390 --> 13:25.272
The crowd is turning on Peter.

13:27.134 --> 13:30.558
And they're citing his Galilean accent as evidence against him.

13:30.578 --> 13:34.042
And this time, Peter just owns Jesus with the profane.

13:34.403 --> 13:37.106
He calls down curses upon himself.

13:38.594 --> 13:58.319
This is like swearing on your life that you're not a Christian and inviting God to strike you dead if you're lying, or perhaps more common, intentionally acting so much like the world that to the world you look nothing like Christ.

14:03.926 --> 14:06.930
Where does personal confrontation create enough pressure

14:07.266 --> 14:12.152
that you profane your language or behavior to blend in.

14:16.097 --> 14:24.627
Disowning Jesus starts with being vague, and that slippery slope takes us to an end of profaning our values.

14:27.010 --> 14:36.562
Now for Peter, the turning point comes when the rooster crows, and it actually tells us in Luke's account that Peter at this moment locks eyes with Jesus.

14:38.434 --> 14:47.184
And Peter doesn't just feel bad because he got caught, but because he remembered the word Jesus had spoken.

14:50.267 --> 14:51.649
He recalled the voice of his Lord.

14:53.671 --> 14:56.695
You know, Peter had long recognized Jesus as Lord.

14:57.536 --> 15:03.122
He had that significant moment of saying, you are the son of the living God, a confession that

15:03.234 --> 15:04.556
The church would be built upon.

15:04.816 --> 15:09.403
Unlike Judas, Peter knew he didn't just betray an innocent man.

15:11.687 --> 15:17.335
Peter recognized that he had disowned the very source of life itself and overwhelmed with regret.

15:17.415 --> 15:21.421
He leaves and weeps bitterly over the lost relationship.

15:24.666 --> 15:32.978
But regret alone is limited because, well, it can show the depth of our love.

15:33.666 --> 15:35.650
and the height of our failure.

15:38.174 --> 15:40.037
It can never pay the price of our pride.

15:42.983 --> 15:46.128
Well, Peter was in the courtyard disowning his king to save his own skin.

15:47.591 --> 15:53.762
That very king was inside the courtroom being disowned by the world to save Peter's soul.

15:56.928 --> 15:58.290
So for Christians today,

15:59.010 --> 16:08.039
If you find yourself in a season of regret, weeping bitterly over a slippery slope, perhaps you've found yourself at the bottom of, that you didn't see coming.

16:09.621 --> 16:19.351
Know that your restoration does not depend on the depth of your tears, but the Savior who never took His eyes off you.

16:23.675 --> 16:26.738
Now if you're joining us and you're exploring faith today,

16:29.410 --> 16:39.683
You might be trying to manage your own regret through behavior modification, but real peace is never found in our efforts to change ourselves.

16:40.824 --> 16:46.091
It's found in being known by the one who was disowned in our place.

16:47.613 --> 16:50.617
So will you get to know him today?

16:55.042 --> 16:58.066
Now let's explore the lethal remorse of Judas.

17:00.514 --> 17:12.696
Many years ago, I led a missions trip to Costa Rica, and we partnered with an organization there that worked in a community that was struggling with severe poverty and abuse within the family situations.

17:13.738 --> 17:22.354
And we had a team of about 20 or so teens and young adults, and we were working long days in various settings in the Central America heat that none of us were really used to.

17:23.234 --> 17:31.763
And so at the end of every day to cool off, we would go to the corner store, we would buy a cold drink or an ice cream or some other treat to relax and cool down.

17:33.045 --> 17:41.834
And we didn't really think much about it until about a week in, one of the community leaders came to us and pointed out a negative impact that we didn't realize we were having.

17:43.416 --> 17:52.626
As all of the people of the community watched the, quote, rich Canadians, go down to the corner store and spend more on junk food in a day

17:53.154 --> 17:54.576
than many of them made in a month.

17:56.899 --> 18:05.509
More than this, the store had begun to raise its prices to match our ability to spend, and now the locals couldn't even afford the food there.

18:08.292 --> 18:12.357
We had gone thinking we would serve this community, but it ended up harming it.

18:13.539 --> 18:19.506
And filled with remorse, the entire team gathered every American dollar

18:19.810 --> 18:27.920
Costa Rican Colone, every Canadian dollar we had, pooled it all together, and we gave it to the organization, and we didn't go back to that store.

18:29.702 --> 18:31.103
But the damage was already done.

18:32.125 --> 18:36.290
And the remorse we felt for it couldn't undo that.

18:37.631 --> 18:46.802
In fact, it would take years of pausing youth missions trips and then slowly bringing them back to rebuild that trust with the community.

18:49.058 --> 18:53.865
As chapter 27 opens, the religious leaders have finalized their plans to execute Jesus.

18:54.746 --> 19:04.561
And Judas, who is seemingly present and oddly surprised by this dark turn, it says he's seized with remorse.

19:06.263 --> 19:18.962
But we learn from Judas' story that remorse is among the most spiritually deceptive of human emotions because of its great capacity to masquerade

19:19.234 --> 19:20.255
as repentance.

19:23.500 --> 19:31.772
In ancient Greek, both remorse and repentance begin with the same prefix, this idea of after something happens.

19:31.792 --> 19:33.815
But then they have dramatically different root words.

19:34.436 --> 19:43.389
Remorse that we see attributed to Judas here in this text is often meaning after concern or concern that comes after something.

19:44.470 --> 19:46.994
Whereas repentance is the equivalent of

19:47.426 --> 19:50.169
understanding that comes after something.

19:51.110 --> 20:02.083
Remorse is concerned for the consequences that follow our behavior, but repentance is the changed way of thinking that leads to different action that follows our behavior.

20:02.724 --> 20:07.249
So to a Christian, remorse is actually an emotional dead end.

20:10.012 --> 20:14.738
Where repentance in Christ is a relational you turn.

20:16.354 --> 20:19.399
The difference for Judas, not surprisingly, lay in his heart.

20:21.242 --> 20:35.807
And he write in one of his books about Judas and Christ, suggest that Judas might have been trying to force God's hand, betraying Jesus not to see him killed, but to corner him into finally launching the political revolution that they wanted.

20:37.610 --> 20:40.274
For Judas, Jesus was never Lord.

20:41.378 --> 20:49.632
In fact, Matthew, the author of this text, records the fact that Judas never referred to Jesus as Lord, but only as teacher.

20:49.692 --> 20:59.869
To Judas, Jesus wasn't a relationship that transformed his way of thinking and acting, but a tool to get where he wanted to go in life.

21:01.952 --> 21:05.618
But when his plans left him overwhelmed by a debt that he couldn't pay,

21:06.626 --> 21:12.652
Judas enters into a lethal cycle of three attempts at self-attonement.

21:15.595 --> 21:26.185
First, Judas offers a callous confession to the religious leaders, but that very group that had led him to disown Jesus offers him zero grace in return.

21:28.507 --> 21:30.689
They tell him, that's your responsibility.

21:33.832 --> 21:35.474
It's a stark reminder for us

21:36.354 --> 21:40.922
that the world will lead us into a ditch and not be there for us to pull us out.

21:43.225 --> 21:47.953
And we do the same as Judas when we seek redemption by confessing to the world.

21:50.197 --> 22:02.898
We might settle for personal acknowledgement of our sin, or confiding in a friend or a colleague or a spouse, or perhaps even public ownership of what we've done wrong.

22:04.034 --> 22:05.576
And none of these things are wrong.

22:05.657 --> 22:07.980
In fact, there are good parts to all of them.

22:08.000 --> 22:12.448
They're all important, but none can absolve us before God.

22:13.610 --> 22:18.317
And that's the point.

22:18.337 --> 22:21.202
Second, Judas offers a reproachable refund.

22:22.163 --> 22:25.829
He tries to pay for his sin with the very silver he received to commit it.

22:27.192 --> 22:31.218
He throws the 30 pieces of silver back into the temple

22:33.954 --> 22:39.543
a desperate act to buy back his soul with the currency of his betrayal.

22:39.663 --> 22:47.236
And we do the same when we use the currency of our compromise to try and purchase a piece that only Christ can provide.

22:47.797 --> 22:58.514
Like, for example, tithing to the church out of dishonest gain or volunteering the time that we never spend with Jesus.

22:59.938 --> 23:04.605
or mentoring someone from a position that we got by stepping on others to get there.

23:06.527 --> 23:07.389
Or how about this one?

23:08.951 --> 23:14.999
Becoming hyper-religious after a season of lax spiritual disciplines.

23:20.067 --> 23:22.871
Third, Judas offers a permanent price.

23:24.152 --> 23:25.234
He takes his own life.

23:27.170 --> 23:30.635
It's the final desperate act of self-attonement.

23:30.655 --> 23:35.643
He attempts to pay the ultimate debt with the only thing that he has left himself.

23:38.447 --> 23:49.985
Now, most of us would not go to this extreme, but we are very prone to a different attempt to sacrifice our life to atone for our sin.

23:50.886 --> 23:56.274
And that is spending our lives trying to make up for our past

23:56.546 --> 23:58.088
through our own good works.

24:00.372 --> 24:07.563
We might not be dying for our sin, but we are attempting to offer our life as payment.

24:09.206 --> 24:10.769
And the result is the same.

24:12.151 --> 24:16.397
It costs us our life, and it's not enough.

24:21.646 --> 24:24.370
So remorse can reveal the depth of our debt

24:25.026 --> 24:27.210
but it can never afford the price of our redemption.

24:28.292 --> 24:35.103
It does lead us to the end of ourselves, but apart from a savior, the end of ourselves, like Judas, is a dead end.

24:36.786 --> 24:48.466
Remorse alone is lethal because it drives us to look inward for a solution to our sin that can only be found upward in the atoning work of Christ.

24:50.370 --> 24:56.556
Judas tried to force God's hand with a human strategy, and when it failed, he tried to pay the debt with his own life.

24:56.936 --> 25:08.207
But God's good news for all is that we don't have to pay for our sins with our lives because Jesus paid with his.

25:13.813 --> 25:19.378
If you are a follower of Jesus, stop trying to buy back God's favor.

25:19.650 --> 25:22.433
with your guilt.

25:22.453 --> 25:27.338
The silver for your betrayal has already been paid by Christ on the cross.

25:29.401 --> 25:41.454
So take the path of repentance instead, where you allow your relationship with Christ to transform the way that you think and the way that you act to be in alignment with Him.

25:43.496 --> 25:45.618
And if you're seeking Jesus today,

25:46.946 --> 25:54.820
Remorse will tell you that you are your own responsibility, but that is a lethal lie.

25:57.385 --> 26:06.621
Jesus has taken the responsibility for your sin upon himself so that you can live forgiven.

26:10.147 --> 26:11.570
Will you trust him for that today?

26:16.322 --> 26:19.206
Finally, let's look at how redemption is liberating.

26:21.269 --> 26:27.518
As a 17-year-old driver in my parents' car, I got into a car accident, and it was my fault.

26:28.480 --> 26:29.882
I had a car full of young people.

26:29.922 --> 26:31.284
We were on the way to the lake.

26:31.965 --> 26:34.509
We were passing through a small town and stop-and-go traffic.

26:35.350 --> 26:38.615
And I was distracted and went right in the back of another car.

26:39.736 --> 26:40.978
The airbags deployed.

26:41.410 --> 26:48.220
And so if you've ever been in that situation, you know that your eyes, your ears, your mouth, everything gets filled with the powder of the airbags.

26:49.041 --> 26:53.206
And so my eyes are watering and teary and I can't hear and my ears are ringing.

26:54.448 --> 27:01.498
And then I look over and discover that my friend in the passenger seat, his wrist has been broken by the airbag deploying it into his forehead.

27:02.980 --> 27:07.186
So he has to go off and get a cast and I sit with the police for a while.

27:08.130 --> 27:14.117
And as I sit in the back of the cruiser and give my report and things like that, it felt like an eternity.

27:15.238 --> 27:16.439
Well, eventually they let me go.

27:16.459 --> 27:27.712
And I got back in the car, which was deemed safe enough to drive home, went and called my father, admitted to him what had happened, and picked up my friend with his fresh cast on his wrist.

27:29.354 --> 27:34.239
Unbeknownst to us, however, the initial impact had sheared off the hood latch.

27:35.561 --> 27:36.722
So on the way home,

27:36.834 --> 27:45.763
at about 100 kilometers per hour on the highway, the wind caught the hood and smashed it in on us through the windshield and the roof.

27:47.485 --> 27:55.372
Mercifully, I was able to peer through the little gap remaining to steer over to the side of the highway where we put the car in park.

27:56.213 --> 28:01.659
I got out and broke down in tears and called my dad a second time to tell him what had happened.

28:02.660 --> 28:05.042
And I remember the relief when my dad showed up.

28:05.762 --> 28:11.312
Because this whole situation was so far outside of my ability to fix it.

28:12.834 --> 28:14.257
My dad came and brought us home.

28:15.459 --> 28:19.286
He had to buy a new car and he dealt with all the insurance.

28:22.652 --> 28:28.562
You know, we all need somebody outside of ourselves to save us.

28:30.562 --> 28:40.520
If we read these stories of Peter and Judas for some kind of redemptive to-do list or don't-do list, we will have missed the point of this scripture altogether.

28:41.422 --> 28:54.546
Because the central figure in both of these men's stories is Jesus, and Matthew's gospel is telling these stories in order to point us not to Judas and not to Peter, but to Christ.

28:58.370 --> 29:01.876
Redemption is a rescue that comes from outside of ourselves.

29:03.239 --> 29:22.514
Just as my dad arrived to take responsibility and settle the insurance and bring us home, Jesus was moving towards the cross in these stories to do what Judas and Peter could not do for themselves, to do what we could never do for ourselves.

29:25.378 --> 29:35.471
While Peter is busy denying him and Judas is busy betraying him, Jesus was the only one moving to secure the price of admission into his kingdom.

29:36.913 --> 29:43.001
And there are two passages in the Bible that speak specifically to what leads us to repentance.

29:43.742 --> 29:46.565
And both note the centrality of God.

29:46.585 --> 29:53.394
2 Corinthians 7 verse 10 says, Godly sorrow leads us to repentance.

29:54.946 --> 30:01.973
This is deep and spirit-led transforming the heart and leading us to hope and reconciliation with God.

30:02.573 --> 30:08.639
Unlike worldly sorrow that we see here, which focuses on self-pity and fear of punishment.

30:10.801 --> 30:17.748
And Romans 2 verse 4 says that the kindness of God leads us to repentance.

30:17.768 --> 30:23.794
This is God's patience and mercy and love that softens our hearts toward Him

30:23.906 --> 30:29.273
and toward his ways as opposed to shame and condemnation and judgment.

30:31.757 --> 30:34.841
In both cases, the first active agent is God.

30:36.704 --> 30:45.836
And this is why worldly regret and remorse are inadequate because they ignore the saving central figure of all of our stories.

30:51.144 --> 30:52.786
The one who moved toward us

30:54.434 --> 30:58.079
for salvation, even while we were disowning Him.

31:00.442 --> 31:03.165
This is the shared realization between Peter and Judas.

31:03.606 --> 31:11.075
Both men were left with the crushing truth that they had exhausted their own capacity to make things right.

31:13.759 --> 31:15.321
Peter's regret wasn't enough.

31:17.183 --> 31:18.685
Sure, he wept bitterly.

31:18.705 --> 31:20.147
It was sincere.

31:20.187 --> 31:22.610
It was gut-wrenching grief.

31:23.618 --> 31:26.222
but his tears couldn't undo his denial.

31:27.724 --> 31:33.974
He couldn't weep his way back into right relationship with Jesus anymore than he could swing the sword to enter his kingdom.

31:38.782 --> 31:41.186
Judas's remorse wasn't enough.

31:42.828 --> 31:48.978
Though he was seized with it and confessed his sin and tried to return the prophet as of his betrayal,

31:50.210 --> 31:53.954
His remorse could not undo the condemnation of Jesus.

31:54.675 --> 31:57.658
He couldn't pay for his sin with his silver or with his life.

31:59.020 --> 32:11.073
And so neither the limited regret that we see with Peter in the courtyard nor the lethal remorse that we see with Judas in the temple contained the power of salvation.

32:14.636 --> 32:19.762
Because neither man could see yet how Christ would overcome their sin.

32:21.538 --> 32:24.341
And Peter would find his forgiveness in Christ.

32:26.403 --> 32:27.965
Judas would never get the chance.

32:31.649 --> 32:35.473
See, redemption isn't what we offer God to make up for our past.

32:37.456 --> 32:46.866
It is a credited gift of righteousness that we didn't earn and a rescue we didn't initiate.

32:49.218 --> 33:00.033
Redemption is liberating because it doesn't come through the depth of our own despair, but through the sufficiency of our Savior.

33:04.719 --> 33:06.401
Jesus became the disowned king.

33:09.906 --> 33:15.794
In the courtyard, he was disowned by his friend, in the courtroom, disowned by his people, and on the cross.

33:17.250 --> 33:21.416
in some way that perhaps we don't fully grasp disowned by his Father in heaven.

33:23.498 --> 33:30.848
Also that we who put our faith in him would not be disowned, but forever called God's own.

33:33.392 --> 33:40.521
Redemption begins when you stop trying to negotiate with God using your regret and your remorse.

33:45.267 --> 33:47.250
So let's look at some application for this week.

33:49.058 --> 33:52.182
Take a inventory of allegiance.

33:54.505 --> 34:02.837
Where have you been vague to avoid the social cost of following Jesus?

34:04.539 --> 34:13.712
And ask the Holy Spirit to help you identify even just one place where you could move from disowning Jesus to publicly confessing him.

34:17.637 --> 34:18.418
But also,

34:19.586 --> 34:21.288
rest in the credited gift.

34:23.070 --> 34:33.781
If you are carrying the weight of past failure, remind yourself daily, however it works for you, that your debt is not your responsibility anymore.

34:34.402 --> 34:38.626
It has been settled by the King who was disowned for you.

34:43.251 --> 34:46.034
Now, if you have yet to put your faith in Christ,

34:47.298 --> 34:59.838
Perhaps what drew you here today or drew you to watch online was that up until now, you might have been living under this heavy weight of being your own responsibility.

35:00.820 --> 35:09.294
You've likely felt the pressure to fix the wreck of your own life or pay for your own mistakes or manage your own guilt.

35:10.375 --> 35:14.482
But today, the disowned king offers you a different way.

35:18.914 --> 35:21.357
because he was cast out so that you could be brought in.

35:22.739 --> 35:27.405
He isn't asking you to clean up your life or promise that you won't ever fail again.

35:27.445 --> 35:33.534
He is inviting you to stop negotiating and start trusting him.

35:40.062 --> 35:48.754
He took the responsibility for your sin on the cross so that you could live for the first time, truly forgiven.

35:51.106 --> 35:56.093
Will you stop trying to save yourself and let the king bring you home?

35:59.178 --> 36:06.549
Because regret is limited and remorse can be lethal, but redemption is liberating.

36:08.712 --> 36:09.193
Let's pray.

36:15.382 --> 36:18.226
Lord Jesus, thank you for being the disowned king.

36:19.522 --> 36:21.364
who pays the price that we could not afford.

36:21.404 --> 36:33.680
Help us to live this week not in the limitation of our regret or the lethality of our remorse, but in the total liberation of your redemptive work in our lives.

36:35.141 --> 36:45.634
And make us your church here at Foothills, a people who aren't vague or embarrassed by the relationship we have with you, but who share Jesus boldly.

36:47.297 --> 36:48.498
It's in your name we pray.

36:49.378 --> 36:52.046
Amen.

